      <hedline>
        <hl1>Tired of Being Wired</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arnold Ahlert letter on Alan Ehrenhalt's May 7 Op-Ed article on electronic revolution says people will become tired of being 'wired in' all the time</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Alan Ehrenhalt (''Are We as Happy as We Think?'', Op-Ed, May 7) offers the assumption that being ''extremely connected'' with regard to the electronic revolution is inherently desirable.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Alan Ehrenhalt (''Are We as Happy as We Think?'', Op-Ed, May 7) offers the assumption that being ''extremely connected'' with regard to the electronic revolution is inherently desirable.</p>
        <p>What if it's not? Isn't it possible that people will get tired of being ''wired in'' all the time? We are already beginning to see social sanctions regarding the use of cell phones.</p>
        <p>It might take a few years, but maybe someday in the near future,  those who consider themselves to be trend-setters might rediscover the virtues of a little peace and quiet.</p>
        <p>ARNOLD AHLERT  Boca Raton, Fla., May 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
